member.name: T:pwiz.CLI.msdata.ChromatogramList
member.summary:
Interface for accessing chromatograms, which may be stored in memory or backed by a data file (RAW, mzXML, mzML).
- Implementations are expected to keep a chromatogram index in the form of List<ChromatogramIdentity> or equivalent. The default find*() functions search the index linearly. Implementations may provide constant time indexing.
- The semantics of chromatogram() may vary slightly with implementation. In particular, a ChromatogramList implementation that is backed by a file may choose either to cache or discard the Chromatogram for future access, with the caveat that the client may write to the underlying data.
- It is the implementation's responsibility to return a valid Chromatogram from chromatogram(). If this cannot be done, an exception must be thrown.
- The 'getBinaryData' flag is a hint if false: implementations may provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on chromatogram(index, false); implementations *must* provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on chromatogram(index, true).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_electronvolt
member.summary: electronvolt: A non-SI unit of energy (eV) defined as the energy acquired by a single unbound electron when it passes through an electrostatic potential difference of one volt. An electronvolt is equal to 1.602 176 53(14) x 10^-19 J.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt_per_meter_kelvin
member.summary: watt per meter kelvin: An heat conduction unit which is equal to one watt divided by meter kelvin.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_siemens

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_heat_conduction_unit
member.summary: heat conduction unit: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of the spontaneous transfer of thermal energy through matter, from a region of higher temperature to a region of lower temperature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_electrical_conduction_unit

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_conduction_unit
member.summary: conduction unit: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of the transmission of an entity through a medium.

member.summary: effective dose unit:

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_decibel

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_poise
member.summary: poise: A viscosity unit which is equal to one dyne second per square centimeter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pascal_second
member.summary: pascal second: A viscosity unit which is equal to one pascale per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_viscosity_unit

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dyne_per_cm

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_newton_per_meter

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pixels_per_inch
member.summary: pixels per inch: A spatial resolution unit which is a standard measure of the resolution of a computer display, related to the size of the display in inches and the total number of pixels in the horizontal and vertical directions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_micron
member.summary: micron: A spatial resolution unit which is equal to a pixel size of one micrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dots_per_inch
member.summary: dots per inch: A spatial resolution unit which is a standard measure of the printing resolution, in particular the number of individual dots of ink a printer or toner can produce within a linear one-inch space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_spatial_resolution_unit
member.summary: spatial resolution unit: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the way luminance and chrominance may be sampled at different levels.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dynamic_range_unit
member.summary: dynamic range unit: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the amount of contrast available in a pixel.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_chroma_sampling_unit
member.summary: chroma sampling unit: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the amount of spatial detail in an image.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_image_resolution_unit
member.summary: image resolution unit: An information unit which is a standard measure of the detail an image holds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_megabyte
member.summary: megabyte: An information unit which is equal to 1000 kB.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilobyte
member.summary: kilobyte: An information unit which is equal to 1000 bytes.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_byte
member.summary: byte: An information unit which is equal to 8 bits.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_bit
member.summary: bit: An information unit which refers to a digit in the binary numeral system, which consists of base 2 digits (ie there are only 2 possible values: 0 or 1).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_information_unit
member.summary: information unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of information.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilovolt_hour
member.summary: kilovolt-hour: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to one thousand volt-hours.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_volt_hour
member.summary: volt-hour: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to 3600 Wb.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_tesla
member.summary: tesla: A magnetic flux density unit which is equal to one weber per square meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_magnetic_flux_density
member.summary: magnetic flux density: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the strength of a magnetic field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_weber
member.summary: weber: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to the amount of flux that when linked with a single turn of wire for an interval of one second will induce an electromotive force of one volt.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_magnetic_flux
member.summary: magnetic flux: A derived unit which is a standard measure of quantity of magnetism, taking account of the strength and the extent of a magnetic field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilowatt_hour
member.summary: kilowatt-hour: An energy unit which is equal to 1,000 watt-hours.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt_hour
member.summary: watt-hour: An energy unit which is equal to the amount of electrical energy equivalent to a one-watt load drawing power for one hour.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilodalton
member.summary: kilodalton: A mass unit which is equal to one thousand daltons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dalton
member.summary: dalton: An independently to the base SI units defined mass unit which is equal to one twelfth of the mass of an unbound atom of the carbon-12 nuclide, at rest and in its ground state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_coulomb
member.summary: coulomb: An electrical charge unit which is equal to the amount of charge transferred by a current of 1 ampere in 1 second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_electric_charge
member.summary: electric charge: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity of unbalanced electricity in a body (either positive or negative) and construed as an excess or deficiency of electrons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_volt
member.summary: volt: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to the work per unit charge. One volt is the potential difference required to move one coulomb of charge between two points in a circuit while using one joule of energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_electric_potential_difference
member.summary: electric potential difference: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the work done per unit charge as a charge is moved between two points in an electric field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_disintegrations_per_second
member.summary: disintegrations per second: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_plaque_forming_unit_per_milliliter
member.summary: plaque forming unit per milliliter: A concentration unit which a measure of plague forming units in one milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_plaque_forming_unit_per_volume
member.summary: plaque forming unit per volume: A concentration unit which a measure of plague forming units in a given volume.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_colony_forming_unit_per_milliliter
member.summary: colony forming unit per milliliter: A colony forming unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers in one milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_colony_forming_unit_per_volume
member.summary: colony forming unit per volume: A concentration unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers in a given volume.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_plaque_forming_unit
member.summary: plaque forming unit: A dimensionless count unit which a measure of plague forming units in a given volume.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_colony_forming_unit
member.summary: colony forming unit: A dimensionless count unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_deciliter
member.summary: deciliter: A volume unit which is equal to one tenth of a liter or 10^[-1] L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_gram_per_deciliter
member.summary: gram per deciliter: A mass density unit which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in deciliters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_milliliter_per_liter
member.summary: milliliter per liter: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one liter of solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_milliliter_per_cubic_meter
member.summary: milliliter per cubic meter: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one cubic meter of solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_volume_per_unit_volume
member.summary: volume per unit volume: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the given volume of the solute in the total volume of the resulting solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_katal_per_liter
member.summary: katal per liter: A catalytic (activity) concentration unit which is equal to 1 katal activity of a catalyst in a given volume of one thousandth of a cubic meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_katal_per_cubic_meter
member.summary: katal per cubic meter: A catalytic (activity) concentration unit which is equal to 1 katal activity of a catalyst in a given volume of one cubic meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_catalytic__activity__concentration_unit
member.summary: catalytic (activity) concentration unit: A concentration unit which is a standard measure of the amount of the action of a catalyst in a given volume.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_cells_per_milliliter
member.summary: cells per milliliter: A unit of cell concentration which is equal to one cell in a volume of 1 milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_cell_concentration_unit
member.summary: cell concentration unit: A concentration unit which denotes the average cell number in a given volume.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_microliter_per_kilogram
member.summary: microliter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-6] l/kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_milliliter_per_kilogram
member.summary: milliliter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to a thousandth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-3] l/kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_liter_per_kilogram
member.summary: liter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to one liter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pH
member.summary: pH: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the acidity of a solution in terms of activity of hydrogen ions (H+).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_degree_fahrenheit
member.summary: degree fahrenheit: A temperature derived unit which is equal to 5/9ths of a kelvin. Negative 40 degrees Fahrenheit is equal to negative 40 degrees Celsius.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_confluence_percentage
member.summary: confluence percentage: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the density of an attached or monolayer culture (e.g., cell culture).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_purity_percentage
member.summary: purity percentage: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the homogeneity of a biomaterial.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_molecule_count
member.summary: molecule count: A dimensionless count unit which denotes the number of molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_fraction
member.summary: fraction: A dimensionless ratio unit which relates the part (the numerator) to the whole (the denominator).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_ratio
member.summary: ratio: A dimensionless unit which denotes an amount or magnitude of one quantity relative to another.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_count
member.summary: count: A dimensionless unit which denotes a simple count of things.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pi
member.summary: pi: A dimensionless unit which denoted an irrational real number, approximately equal to 3.14159 which is the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter in Euclidean geometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_percent
member.summary: percent: A dimensionless ratio unit which denotes numbers as fractions of 100.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dimensionless_unit
member.summary: dimensionless unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of physical quantity consisting of only a numerical number without any units.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_degree
member.summary: degree: A plane angle unit which is equal to 1/360 of a full rotation or 1.7453310^[-2] rad.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_meter
member.summary: kilogram per meter: An area density unit which is equal to the mass of an object in kilograms divided by one meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_linear_density_unit
member.summary: linear density unit: A density unit which is a standard measure of the mass exerting an influence on a one-dimensional object.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_density_unit
member.summary: density unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the influence exerted by some mass.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_enzyme_unit
member.summary: enzyme unit: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the amount of the enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of 1 micro mole of substrate per minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_mass_per_unit_volume
member.summary: mass per unit volume: A concentration unit which is a standard measure of the mass of a substance in a given volume (density).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_unit_per_liter
member.summary: unit per liter: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one liter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_unit_per_milliliter
member.summary: unit per milliliter: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_unit_per_volume_unit
member.summary: unit per volume unit: A derived concentration unit which is a standard measure of the number of units, as an agreed arbitrary amount, of a given substance per a specific volume of solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_milligram_per_milliliter
member.summary: milligram per milliliter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in milligrams divided by the volume in milliliters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_gram_per_liter
member.summary: gram per liter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in liters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_liter
member.summary: kilogram per liter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in kilograms divided by the volume in liters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_gram_per_milliliter
member.summary: gram per milliliter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_quadrillion
member.summary: parts per quadrillion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[15].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_trillion
member.summary: parts per trillion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[12].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_billion
member.summary: parts per billion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[9].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_million
member.summary: parts per million: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[6].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_thousand
member.summary: parts per thousand: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_hundred
member.summary: parts per hundred: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 100 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_parts_per_notation
member.summary: parts per notation: A dimensionless concentration notation which describes the amount of one substance in another. It is the ratio of the amount of the substance of interest to the amount of that substance plus the amount of the substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_volume_percentage
member.summary: volume percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the volume of the solute in mL per 100 mL of the resulting solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_mass_volume_percentage
member.summary: mass volume percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of the substance in a mixture as a percentage of the volume of the entire mixture.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_mass_percentage
member.summary: mass percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of a substance in a mixture as a percentage of the mass of the entire mixture.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt_per_steradian
member.summary: watt per steradian: A radiant intensity unit which is equal to one kilogram meter squared per second cubed per steradian.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_radiance_unit
member.summary: radiance unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation through space or through a material medium in the form of electromagnetic waves.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_microeinstein_per_square_meter_per_second
member.summary: microeinstein per square meter per second: An irradiance unit which is equal to one microeinstein per square meter per second or 10^[-6] microeinstein/sm^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_radiant_intensity_unit
member.summary: radiant intensity unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of electromagnetic radiation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt_per_steradian_per_square_meter
member.summary: watt per steradian per square meter: A radiance unit which is equal to one watt of radiant power incident per steradian solid angle per one square meter projected area of the source, as viewed from the given direction.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_light_unit
member.summary: light unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of light.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_einstein_per_square_meter_per_second
member.summary: einstein per square meter per second: An irradiance unit which is equal to one einstein per square meter per second. One einstein is one mole of photons, regardless of their frequency. Therefore, the number of photons in an einstein is Avogadro's number.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt_per_square_meter
member.summary: watt per square meter: An irradiance unit which is equal to 1 watt of radiant power incident per one square meter surface area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_irradiance_unit
member.summary: irradiance unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation at a surface, per unit area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_foot_candle
member.summary: foot candle: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 foot^[2]. One footcandle is equal to 10.76 lux.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_half_life
member.summary: half life: A time unit which represents the period over which the activity or concentration of a specified chemical or element falls to half its original activity or concentration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_century
member.summary: century: A time unit which is equal to 100 years.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_nanosecond
member.summary: nanosecond: A time unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a second or 10^[-9] s.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_time_derived_unit
member.summary: time derived unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the dimension in which events occur in sequence.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_counts_per_minute
member.summary: counts per minute: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the number of light emissions produced by ionizing radiation in one minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_disintegrations_per_minute
member.summary: disintegrations per minute: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per minute or there is one atom disintegration per minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_microcurie
member.summary: microcurie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one millionth of a curie or 10^[-6] Ci.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_millicurie
member.summary: millicurie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one thousandth of a curie or 10^[-3] Ci.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_nanosievert
member.summary: nanosievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a sievert or 10^[-9] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_nanogray
member.summary: nanogray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a gray or 10^[-9] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_milligray
member.summary: milligray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gray or 10^[-3] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_microgray
member.summary: microgray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one millionth of a gray or 10^[-6] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_Roentgen_equivalent_man
member.summary: Roentgen equivalent man: A dose equivalent unit which when multiplied by hundred is equal to one sievert or 1 Sv. 1 Sv is equal to 100 rem.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_microsievert
member.summary: microsievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one millionth of a sievert or 10^[-6] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_millisievert
member.summary: millisievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a sievert or 10^[-3] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_sievert
member.summary: sievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_roentgen
member.summary: roentgen: An exposure unit which is equal to the amount of radiation required to liberate positive and negative charges of one electrostatic unit of charge in 1 cm^[3] of air at standard temperature and pressure (STP). This corresponds to the generation of approximately 2.0810^[9] ion pairs.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_rad
member.summary: rad: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to 0.01 gray (Gy).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_gray
member.summary: gray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_curie
member.summary: curie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which there are 3.7 x 10^[10] atom disintegration per second (dps).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_becquerel
member.summary: becquerel: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second (dps).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_exposure_unit
member.summary: exposure unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity that expresses the ability of radiation to ionize air and thereby create electric charges which can be collected and measured.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_dose_equivalent_unit
member.summary: dose equivalent unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the expression of dose in terms of its biological effect.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_absorbed_dose_unit
member.summary: absorbed dose unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the energy imparted by ionizing radiation to unit mass of matter such as tissue.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_activity__of_a_radionuclide__unit
member.summary: activity (of a radionuclide) unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the transformation (disintegration) rate of a radioactive substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_radiation_unit
member.summary: radiation unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of radiation emitted by a given radiation source as well as the amount of radiation absorbed or deposited in a specific material by a radiation source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_temperature_derived_unit
member.summary: temperature derived unit: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of temperature in a particular temperature scale.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_steradian
member.summary: steradian: A solid angle unit which is equal to the solid angle subtended at the center of a sphere by an area on the surface of the sphere that is equal to the radius squared.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_solid_angle_unit
member.summary: solid angle unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by three or more planes intersecting at a common point.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_radian
member.summary: radian: A plane angle unit which is equal to the angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc equal in length to the radius of the circle, approximately 57 degrees 17 minutes and 44.6 seconds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_plane_angle_unit
member.summary: plane angle unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by two straight lines in the same plane.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_angle_unit
member.summary: angle unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the figure or space formed by the junction of two lines or planes.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_katal
member.summary: katal: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the activity of a catalyst in moles per second, such as the amount of an enzyme needed to transform one mole of substrate per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_catalytic_activity_unit
member.summary: catalytic activity unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of the action of a catalyst.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_lumen
member.summary: lumen: A luminous flux unit which is equal to the luminous flux emitted into 1 steradian by a point source of 1 candela.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_luminous_flux_unit
member.summary: luminous flux unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the flow of radiant energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_lux
member.summary: lux: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_illuminance_unit
member.summary: illuminance unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the luminous flux incident on a unit area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_watt
member.summary: watt: A power unit which is equal to the power used when work is done at the rate of 1 joule per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_power_unit
member.summary: power unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure power or the rate of doing work.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_joule
member.summary: joule: An energy unit which is equal to the energy required when a force of 1 newton moves an object 1 meter in the direction of the force.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_energy_unit
member.summary: energy unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the work done by a certain force (gravitational, electric, magnetic, force of inertia, etc).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pascal
member.summary: pascal: A pressure unit which is equal to the pressure or stress on a surface caused by a force of 1 newton spread over a surface of 1 m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_pressure_unit
member.summary: pressure unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force applied to a given area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_newton
member.summary: newton: A force unit which is equal to the force required to cause an acceleration of 1m/s2 of a mass of 1 Kg in the direction of the force.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.UO_force_unit
member.summary: force unit: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force is applied when a mass is accelerated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_LOWESS_smoothing
member.summary: LOWESS smoothing: Reduces intensity spikes by applying a modeling method known as locally weighted polynomial regression. At each point in the data set a low-degree polynomial is fit to a subset of the data, with explanatory variable values near the point whose response is being estimated. The polynomial is fit using weighted least squares, giving more weight to points near the point whose response is being estimated and less weight to points further away. The value of the regression function for the point is then obtained by evaluating the local polynomial using the explanatory variable values for that data point. The LOESS fit is complete after regression function values have been computed for each of the n data points. Many of the details of this method, such as the degree of the polynomial model and the weights, are flexible.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Savitzky_Golay_smoothing
member.summary: Savitzky-Golay smoothing: Reduces intensity spikes by applying local polynomial regression (of degree k) on a distribution (of at least k+1 equally spaced points) to determine the smoothed value for each point. It tends to preserve features of the distribution such as relative maxima, minima and width, which are usually 'flattened' by other adjacent averaging techniques.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_selected_reaction_monitoring_spectrum
member.summary: SRM spectrum: Spectrum obtained when data are acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z values of selected precursor ions a recorded via two or more stages of mass spectrometry. The precursor/product ion pair is called a transition pair. Data can be obtained for a single transition pair or multiple transition pairs. Multiple time segments of different transition pairs can exist in a single file. Single precursor ions can have multiple product ions consitituting multiple transition pairs. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed as tandem mass spectrometry in time or tandem mass spectrometry in space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_orbitrap
member.summary: orbitrap: An ion trapping device that consists of an outer barrel-like electrode and a coaxial inner spindle-like electrode that form an electrostatic field with quadro-logarithmic potential distribution. The frequency of harmonic oscillations of the orbitally trapped ions along the axis of the electrostatic field is independent of the ion velocity and is inversely proportional to the square root of m/z so that the trap can be used as a mass analyzer.

member.summary: 1200 series LC/MSD VL: The LC/MSD VL ion trap is part of the family of Agilent ion trap mass spectrometers. It has ESI, APCI and APPI ion sources and is a useful ion trap when the amount of sample is not the limiting factor.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6410_Triple_Quad_LC_MS
member.summary: 6410 Triple Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6410 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a Agilent triple quadrupole mass spectrometer. Mass range of the mass spectrometer is 15-1650 m/z, resolution is at three settings of 0.7 u (unit), 1.2 u (wide) and 2.5 u (widest). The mass accuracy for 6410 mass spectrometer is 0.1 across the mass range. The collision cell is a hexapole with linear acceleration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6210_Time_of_Flight_LC_MS
member.summary: 6210 Time-of-Flight LC/MS: The 6210 Time-of-Flight LC/MS is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a Agilent time of flight mass spectrometer. This time of flight mass spectrometer has a m/z range of 50-12000, mass accuracy of less than 2 ppm and resolution greater than 13,000 at m/z 2722. It has multiple ion sources and can be used with multimode ion sources.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6140_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6140 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6140 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 Series of Agilent quadrupole mass spectrometers. 6140 Quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 10-1350, 2500 u/s scan speed in standard mode and 10000 u/s speed in fast-scan mode. It also uses multiple signal acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6130_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6130 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6130 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 series of Agilent mass spectrometers. The 6130 quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 2-3000, 2500 u/s scan speed in standard mode and 5250 u/s speed in fast-scan mode. It also uses multiple signal acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6120_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6120 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6120 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 Series of Agilent mass spectrometers. 6120 quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 10-1500, 2500 u/s scan speed and utilizes multiple signal acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_6110_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6110 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6110 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with an entry level single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 Series of Agilent quadrupole mass spectrometers. 6110 Quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 10-1500 and 2500 u/s scan speed. It proves useful for wide range of SIM quantitative applications.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_1200_series_LC_MSD_SL
member.summary: 1200 series LC/MSD SL: The 1200 Series LC/MSD SL ion trap belongs to the Agilent LC/MSD ion trap family. It provides fast polarity switching and multisignal data acquisition capabilities in a single run while also providing 5 stages of automated data dependent MS/MS and 11 stages of manual MS/MS.

member.summary: mass analyzer type: Mass analyzer separates the ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_spectrum
member.summary: spectrum: A mass spectrum is an intensity vs m/z (mass-to-charge ratio) plot representing a chemical analysis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_unimolecular_dissociation
member.summary: unimolecular dissociation: Fragmentation reaction in which the molecularity is treated as one, irrespective of whether the dissociative state is that of a metastable ion produced in the ion source or results from collisional excitation of a stable ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_surface_induced_reaction
member.summary: surface-induced reaction: A process wherein a reactant ion interacts with a surface to produce either chemically different species or a change in the internal energy of the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_superelastic_collision
member.summary: superelastic collision: Collision in which the translational energy of the fast-moving collision partner is increased at the expense of internal energy of one or both collision partners.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_reaction
member.summary: ion reaction: Chemical transformation involving an ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_partial_charge_transfer_reaction
member.summary: partial charge transfer reaction: Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some but not all of the ion charge is transferred to the neutral.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Multiphoton_Dissociation
member.summary: photodissociation: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_photodissociation
member.summary: photodissociation: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_McLafferty_Rearrangement
member.summary: McLafferty Rearrangement: A dissociation reaction triggered by transfer of a hydrogen atom via a 6-member transition state to the formal radical/charge site from a carbon atom four atoms removed from the charge/radical site (the gamma-carbon); subsequent rearrangement of electron density leads to expulsion of an olefin molecule. This term was originally applied to ketone ions where the charge/radical site is the carbonyl oxygen, but it is now more widely applied.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_low_energy_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: low-energy collision-induced dissociation: A collision-induced dissociation process wherein the precursor ion has the translational energy lower than approximately 1000 eV. This process typically requires multiple collisions and the collisional excitation is cumulative.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_low_energy_collisions
member.summary: low energy collisions: A collision between an ion and neutral species with translational energy approximately 1000 eV or lower.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_kinetic_method
member.summary: kinetic method: An approach to determination of ion thermodynamic quantities by a bracketing procedure in which the relative probabilities of competing ion fragmentations are measured via the relative abundances of the reaction products. The extended kinetic method takes the associated entropy changes into account.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_exchange_reaction
member.summary: ion/neutral species exchange reaction: In this reaction an association reaction is accompanied by the subsequent or simultaneous liberation of a different neutral species as a product.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_reaction
member.summary: ion/neutral species reaction: A process wherein a charged species interacts with a neutral reactant to produce either chemically different species or changes in the internal energy of one or both of the reactants.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_complex
member.summary: ion/neutral complex: A particular type of transition state that lies between precursor and product ions on the reaction coordinate of some ion reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_molecule_reaction
member.summary: ion/molecule reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral molecule. The term ion-molecule reaction is not recommended because the hyphen suggests a single species that is that is both an ion and a molecule.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ionizing_collision
member.summary: ionizing collision: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which one or more electrons are removed from either the ion or neutral.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_energy_loss_spectrum
member.summary: ion energy loss spectrum: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function their loss of translational energy in reactions with neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_hydrogen_deuterium_exchange
member.summary: hydrogen/deuterium exchange: Exchange of hydrogen atoms with deuterium atoms in a molecule or pre-formed ion in solution prior to introduction into a mass spectrometer, or by reaction of an ion with a deuterated collision gas inside a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_homolytic_cleavage
member.summary: homolytic cleavage: Fragmentation of an odd electron ion that results from one of a pair of electrons that form a bond between two atoms moving to form a pair with the odd electron on the atom at the apparent charge site. Fragmentation results in the formation of an even electron ion and a radical. This reaction involves the movement of a single electron and is symbolized by a single-barbed arrow. Synonymous with Homolysis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_high_energy_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: high-energy collision-induced dissociation: A collision-induced dissociation process wherein the projectile ion has the translational energy higher than approximately 1000 eV.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_high_energy_collision
member.summary: high energy collision: Collision-induced dissociation process wherein the projectile ion has laboratory-frame translational energy higher than 1 keV.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_heterolytic_cleavage
member.summary: heterolytic cleavage: Fragmentation of a molecule or ion in which both electrons forming the single bond that is broken remain on one of the atoms that were originally bonded. This term is synonymous with heterolysis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_collision_gas
member.summary: collision gas: An inert gas used for collisional excitation. The term target gas is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_collisional_excitation
member.summary: collisional excitation: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_transfer_reaction
member.summary: charge transfer reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some or all of the charge of the reactant ion is transferred to the neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_stripping_reaction
member.summary: charge stripping reaction: Reaction of a positive ion with a neutral species in which the positive charge on the product ion is greater than that on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_permutation_reaction
member.summary: charge permutation reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species with a resulting change in the magnitude or sign of the charge on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_reaction
member.summary: charge inversion reaction: Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the charge on the product ion is reversed in sign with respect to the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_induced_fragmentation
member.summary: charge-induced fragmentation: Fragmentation of an odd electron ion in which the cleaved bond is adjacent to the apparent charge site. Synonymous with charge mediated fragmentation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_buffer_gas
member.summary: buffer gas: An inert gas used for collisional deactivation of internally excited ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_beta_cleavage
member.summary: beta-cleavage: A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at an atom removed from the apparent charge site atom by two bonds and an atom adjacent to that atom and removed from the aparent charge site by three bonds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_alpha_cleavage
member.summary: alpha-cleavage: A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at the atom adjacent to the atom at the apparent charge site and an atom removed from the aparent charge site by two bonds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_association_reaction
member.summary: association reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the reactants combine to form a single ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_vertical_ionization
member.summary: vertical ionization: A process in which an electron is removed from or added to a molecule without a change in the positions of the atoms. The resulting ion is typically in an excited vibrational state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_thermal_ionization
member.summary: thermal ionization: The ionization of a neutral species through contact with a high temperature surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_surface_ionization
member.summary: surface ionization: The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_surface_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: surface-assisted laser desorption ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions from molecules that are deposited on a particular surface substrate that is irradiated with a pulsed laser. See also matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_spark_ionization
member.summary: spark ionization: The formation of ions from a solid material by an intermittent electrical discharge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_soft_ionization
member.summary: soft ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions without extensive fragmentation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_secondary_ionization
member.summary: secondary ionization: The process in which ions are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms or ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_pre_ionization_state
member.summary: pre-ionization state: An electronic state capable of undergoing auto-Ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_plasma_desorption_ionization
member.summary: plasma desorption ionization: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_penning_ionization
member.summary: penning ionization: Ionization that occurs through the interaction of two or more neutral gaseous species, at least one of which is internally excited.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nanospray
member.summary: nanoelectrospray: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nanoelectrospray
member.summary: nanoelectrospray: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_microelectrospray
member.summary: microelectrospray: Electrospray ionization at a solvent flow rate of 300-800 nL/min where the flow is a result of a mechanical pump. See nanaoelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_membrane_inlet
member.summary: membrane inlet: A semi-permeable membrane separator that permits the passage of gas sample directly to the mass spectrometer ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_liquid_secondary_ionization
member.summary: liquid secondary ionization: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of ions with a sample that is dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also fast atom bombardment and secondary ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: laser desorption ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions by the interaction of a pulsed laser with a solid or liquid material.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ionization_efficiency
member.summary: ionization efficiency: The ratio of the number of ions formed to the number of electrons, molecules or photons used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_pair_formation
member.summary: ion-pair formation: The reaction of a molecule to form both a positive ion and negative ion fragment among the products.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_desolvation
member.summary: ion desolvation: The removal of solvent molecules clustered around a gas-phase ion by means of heating and/or collisions with gas molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_electron_ionization
member.summary: electron ionization: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_dissociative_ionization
member.summary: dissociative ionization: The reaction of a gas-phase molecule that results in its decomposition to form products, one of which is an ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_desorption_ionization_on_silicon
member.summary: desorption/ionization on silicon: The formation of ions by laser desorption ionization of a sample deposited on a porous silicon surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_chemi_ionization
member.summary: chemi-ionization: The reaction of a neutral molecule with an internally excited molecule to form an ion. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemical ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_exchange_ionization
member.summary: charge exchange ionization: The interaction of an ion with an atom or molecule in which the charge on the ion is transferred to the neutral without the dissociation of either. Synonymous with charge transfer ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_autoionization
member.summary: autoionization: The formation of an ion when an atom or molecule in a discrete state with an energy greater than the ionization threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_autodetachment
member.summary: autodetachment: The formation of a neutral when a negative ion in a disrtete state with an energy greater than the detachment threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_photoionization
member.summary: atmospheric pressure photoionization: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_associative_ionization
member.summary: associative ionization: An ionization process in which two excited atoms or molecules react to form a single positive ion and an electron.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_adiabatic_ionization
member.summary: adiabatic ionization: A process whereby an electron is removed from an atom, ion, or molecule to produce an ion in its lowest energy state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_unstable_ion
member.summary: unstable ion: An ion with sufficient enerrgy to dissociate within the ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_stable_ion
member.summary: stable ion: An ion with internal energy sufficiently low that it does not rearrange or dissociate prior to detection in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_reference_ion
member.summary: reference ion: A stable ion whose structure is known with certainty. These ions are usually formed by direct ionization of a neutral molecule of known structure and are used to verify by comparison the structure of an unknown ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_radical_ion
member.summary: radical ion: An ion, either a cation or anion, containing unpaired electrons in its ground state. The unpaired electron is denoted by a superscript dot alongside the superscript symbol for charge, such as for the molecular ion of a molecule M, that is, M+. Radical ions with more than one charge and/or more than one unpaired electron are denoted such as M(2+)(2). Unless the positions of the unpaired electron and charge can be associated with specific atoms, superscript charge designation should be placed before the superscript dot designation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_protonated_molecule
member.summary: protonated molecule: An ion formed by interaction of a neutral molecule with a proton and represented by the symbol [M + H]+, where M is the neutral molecule. The term 'protonated molecular ion,' 'quasi-molecular ion' and 'pseudo-molecular ion' are not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_positive_ion
member.summary: positive ion: An atomic or molecular species having a net positive electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_principal_ion
member.summary: principal ion: Most abundant ion of an isotope cluster, such as the 11B79Br2 81Br+ ion of m/z 250 of the cluster of isotopologue molecular ions of BBr3. The term principal ion has also been used to describe ions that have been artificially isotopically enriched in one or more positions such as CH3 13CH3+ or CH2D2 +, but those are best defined as isotopologue ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_onium_ion
member.summary: onium ion: A positively charged hypervalent ion of the nonmetallic elements. Examples are the methonium ion CH5+, the hydrogenonium ion H3+ and the hydronium ion H3O+. Other examples are the carbonium, oxonium, sulfonium, nitronium, diazonium, phosphonium, and halonium ions. Onium ions are not limited to monopositive ions; multiply-charged onium ions exist such as the gitonic (proximal) oxonium dication H4O2+ and the distonic oxonium dication H2O+-CH2-CH2-OH2+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_non_classical_ion
member.summary: non-classical ion: Hyper-coordinated carbonium ion such as the penta-coordinated norbornyl cation. Note: Tri-coordinated carbenium ions are termed classical ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_negative_ion
member.summary: negative ion: An atomic or molecular species having a net negative electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_molecular_ion
member.summary: molecular ion: An ion formed by the removal of one or more electrons to form a positive ion or the addition off one or more electrons to form a negative ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_metastable_ion
member.summary: metastable ion: An ion that is formed with internal energy higher than the threshold for dissociation but with a lifetime great enough to allow it to exit the ion source and enter the mass spectrometer where it dissociates before detection.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Isotopomeric_ion
member.summary: Isotopomeric ion: Isomeric ion having the same numbers of each isotopic atom but differing in their positions. Isotopomeric ions can be either configurational isomers in which two atomic isotopes exchange positions or isotopic stereoisomers. The term isotopomer is a shortening of isotopic isomer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Isotopologue_ion
member.summary: Isotopologue ion: An ion that differs only in the isotopic composition of one or more of its constituent atoms. For example CH4+ and CH3D+ or 10BF3 and 11BF3. The term isotopologue is a contraction of isotopic homologue.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_
member.summary: ion?: An atomic or molecular species having a net positive or negative electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_fragment_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: fragment ion: A product ion that results from the dissociation of a precursor ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_enium_ion
member.summary: enium ion: A positively charged lower-valency ion of the nonmetallic elements. The methenium ion is CH3+. Other examples are the oxenium, sulfenium, nitrenium, phosphenium, and halenium ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_distonic_ion
member.summary: distonic ion: A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin cannot be both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms as it can be with a conventional ion. For example, CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion whereas the radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+ is a conventional ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_dimeric_ion
member.summary: dimeric ion: An ion formed by ionization of a dimer or by the association of an ion with its neutral counterpart such as [M2]+ or [M-H-M]+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_diagnostic_ion
member.summary: diagnostic ion: A product ion whose formation reveals structural or compositional information of its precursor. For instance, the phenyl cation in an electron ionization mass spectrum is a diagnostic ion for benzene and derivatives.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Conventional_ion
member.summary: Conventional ion: A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin are both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms, as opposed to the spatially separate electronic configuration of distonic ions. The radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+, in which the charge and spin sites are formally located at the O atom is an example of a conventional ion, whereas .CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_cluster_ion
member.summary: cluster ion: An ion formed by a multi-component atomic or molecular assembly of one or more ions with atoms or molecules, such as [(H20)nH]+, [(NaCl)nNa]+ and [(H3PO3)nHPO3]-.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_cationized_molecule
member.summary: cationized molecule: An ion formed by the association of a cation with a neutral molecule, M, for example [M+ Na]+ and [M + K]+. The terms quasi-molecular ion and pseudo-molecular ion should not be used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_anti_aromatic_ion
member.summary: anti-aromatic ion: A planar cyclic ion with 4n ? electrons and is therefore not aromatic.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_analog_ion
member.summary: analog ion: Ions that have similar chemical valence, for example the acetyl cation CH3-CO+ and the thioacetyl cation CH3-CS+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_aromatic_ion
member.summary: aromatic ion: A planar cyclic ion that obeys the Hckel (4n + 2) rule where n is a positive integer representing the number of conjugated Pi electrons. Charge delocalization leads to greater stability compared to a hypothetical localized structure.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_adduct_ion
member.summary: adduct ion: Ion formed by the interaction of an ion with one or more atoms or molecules to form an ion containing all the constituent atoms of the precursor ion as well as the additional atoms from the associated atoms or molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_secondary_electron
member.summary: secondary electron: Electrons that are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms, ions or photons. WAS IN DETECTOR TYPE. Where should it go?

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_postacceleration_detector
member.summary: postacceleration detector: A detector in which the charged particles are accelerated to a high velocity and impinge on a conversion dynode, emitting secondary electrons. The electrons are accelerated onto a phosphor screen, which emits photons that are in turn detected using a photomultiplier or other photon detector.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_point_collector
member.summary: point collector: A detector in which the ion beam is focused onto a point and the individual ions arrive sequentially.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_ion_to_photon_detector
member.summary: ion-to-photon detector: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn strike a phosphor and the resulting photons are detected by a photomultiplier.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_focal_plane_collector
member.summary: focal plane collector: A detector for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_dynode
member.summary: dynode: One of a series of electrodes in a photomultiplier tube. Such an arrangement is able to amplify the current emitted by the photocathode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_conversion_dynode
member.summary: conversion dynode: A surface that is held at high potential such that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_array_detector
member.summary: array detector: Detector comprising several ion collection elements, arranged in a line or grid where each element is an individual detector.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Progeny_Fragment_Ion
member.summary: progeny ion: A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_progeny_ion
member.summary: progeny ion: A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: product ion spectrum: A mass spectrum recorded from any spectrometer in which the appropriate m/z separation scan function is set to record the product ion or ions of selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_product_ion
member.summary: product ion: An ion formed as the product of a reaction involving a particular precursor ion. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation to form fragment ions, an ion/molecule reaction, or simply involve a change in the number of charges. The term fragment ion is deprecated. The term daughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_precursor_ion_spectrum
member.summary: precursor ion spectrum: Spectrum generated by scanning precursor m/z while monitoring a fixed product m/z

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_precursor_ion
member.summary: precursor ion: An ion that reacts to form particular product ions. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation, ion/molecule reaction, isomerization, or change in charge state. The term parent ion is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nth generation product ion spectrum: The mass spectrum recorded from any mass spectrometer in which the appropriate scan function can be set to record the appropriate generation product ion or ions of m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_scan
member.summary: nth generation product ion scan: The specific scan functions or processes that record the appropriate generation of product ion or ions of any m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion
member.summary: nth generation product ion: Serial product ions from dissociation of selected precursor ions where n refers to the number of stages of dissociation. The term granddaughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_neutral_loss
member.summary: neutral loss: The loss of an uncharged species during a rearrangement process.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Space
member.summary: MS/MS in Space: A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in m/z analyzers separated in space. Specific m/z separation functions are designed such that in one section of the instrument ions are selected, dissociated in an intermediate region, and the product ions are then transmitted to another analyser for m/z separation and data acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Time
member.summary: MS/MS in Time: A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in a single m/z analyzer (such as a Paul Ion Trap or FTMS) in discreet steps over time. Ions in a specific m/z range are selected, dissociated, and the product ions analyzed sequentially in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B_1__E_E0___1_2___E
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant B[1-(E/E0)]^1/2 / E: A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector placed in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed while scanning the magnetic field, B, and electric field, E, simultaneously, so as to maintain the quantity B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a constant neutral mass loss (or gain) spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors. E0 is the electric field required to transmit the singly charged analog of the desired neutral fragment. The term B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E linked scan.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B2_E
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant B2/E: A linked scan performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed and the magnetic field, B, and the electric field, E, are scanned simultaneously so as to maintain the ratio B2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a precursor ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in the field free region preceding the two sectors. The term B2/E linked scan is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_E2_V
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant E2/V: A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector. The electric sector field, E, and the accelerating voltage, V, are scanned simultaneously, so as to maintain the ratio E2/V at a constant value. This linked scan recordss a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region (FFR) preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_linked_scan_at_constant_b_e
member.summary: linked scan at constant b/e: A linked scan at constant B/E may be performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector. The magnetic field B and the electric field E are scanned simultaneously while the accelerating voltage V is held constant, so as to maintain the ratio of the two fields constant. This linked scan may record a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_linked_scan
member.summary: linked scan: A scan in an instrument with two or more m/z analysers or in a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector and one electric sector. Two or more of the analyzers are scanned simultaneously so as to preserve a predetermined relationship between scan parameters to produce a product ion, precursor ion or constant neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_e_2_mass_spectrum
member.summary: e/2 mass spectrum: A mass spectrum obtained using a sector mass spectrometer in which the electric sector field E is set to half the value required to transmit the main ion-beam. This spectrum records the signal from doubly charged product ions of charge-stripping reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_consecutive_reaction_monitoring_OBSOLETE
member.summary: consecutive reaction monitoring: A type of MS/MS experiments with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_mass_loss_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral loss spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral loss spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_mass_gain_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral gain spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral gain spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_Constant_Neutral_Mass_Gain_Scan
member.summary: constant neutral gain scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_scan
member.summary: constant neutral gain scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_scan
member.summary: constant neutral loss scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z decrement.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_mass_spectrum
member.summary: charge inversion mass spectrum: The measurement of the relative abundance of ions that result from a charge inversion reaction as a function of m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_2E_Mass_Spectrum
member.summary: 2E Mass Spectrum: A mass spectrum obtained by setting the electric sector field E to twice the value required to transmit the main ion-beam thereby allowing ions with a kinetic energy-to-charge ratio twice that of the main ion-beam to be transmitted. Product ions resulting from partial charge transfer reactions such as m^2+ + N ? m^+ + N^+ that occur in a collision cell (containing a gas, N) located in a field-free region preceding a magnetic and electric sector combination are detected. When the magnetic sector field B is scanned, a mass spectrum of singly charged product ions of doubly charged precursor ions is obtained.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_static_field
member.summary: static field: An electric or magnetic field that does not change in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_space_charge_effect
member.summary: space charge effect: The mutual repulsion of particles of like charge that limits the current in a charged-particle beam and causes beams or packets of charged particles to expand radially over time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_resonance_ion_ejection
member.summary: resonance ion ejection: A mode of ion ejection in a quadrupole ion trap that relies on a auxiliary radio frequency voltage that is applied to the end-cap electrodes. The voltage is tuned to the secular frequency of a particular ion to eject it.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_orthogonal_extraction
member.summary: orthogonal extraction: The pulsed acceleration of ions perpendicular to their direction of travel into a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. Ions may be extracted from a directional ion source, drift tube or m/z separation stage.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mathieu_stability_diagram
member.summary: mathieu stability diagram: A graphical representation expressed in terms of reduced coordinates that describes charged particle motion in a quadrupole mass filter or quadrupole ion trap mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_selective_instability
member.summary: mass selective instability: A method for selective ejection of ions according to their m/z value in an ion trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_selective_axial_ejection
member.summary: mass selective axial ejection: The use of mass selective instability to eject ions of selected m/z values from an ion trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_scan_m_z_range_
member.summary: scan m/z range?: The limit of m/z over which a mass spectrometer can detect ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_limit
member.summary: mass limit: The m/z value above which ions cannot be detected in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_kinetic_energy_analyzer
member.summary: kinetic energy analyzer: A device for measuring the kinetic energy of charged particles using a retarding field, time-of-flight, or the extent of deflection in an electric or magnetic field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_fringing_field
member.summary: fringing field: The electric or magnetic field that extends from the edge of a sector, lens or other ion optics element.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_first_stability_region
member.summary: first stability region: The region of a Mathieu stability diagram closest to the origin. Ions within this region can traverse the full length of a transmission quadrupole.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_electric_field_strength
member.summary: electric field strength: The magnitude of the force per unit charge at a given point in space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_einzel_lens
member.summary: einzel lens: Three element charged particle lens in which the first and third elements are held at the same voltage. Such a lens produces focusing without changing the translational energy of the particle.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_dynamic_mass_spectrometry
member.summary: dynamic mass spectrometry: A mass spectrometer in which m/z separation using one or more electric fields that vary with time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_cyclotron_motion
member.summary: cyclotron motion: The circular motion of a charged particle moving at velocity v in a magnetic field B that results from the force qvB.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_accelerating_voltage
member.summary: accelerating voltage: The electrical potential used to impart kinetic energy to ions in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_transmission_quadrupole_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: transmission quadrupole mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_tandem_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: tandem mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer designed for mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_sector_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: sector mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer consisting of one or more magnetic sectors for m/z selection in a beam of ions. Such instruments may also have one or more electric sectors for energy selection.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_reflectron
member.summary: reflectron: A time-of-flight mass spectrometer that uses a static electric field to reverse the direction of travel of the ions entering it. A reflectron improves mass resolution by assuring that ions of the same m/z but different kinetic energy arrive at the detector at the same time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_quistor
member.summary: quistor: An abbreviation of quadrupole ion storage trap. This term is synonymous with Paul Ion Trap. If so then add a synonym to paul and obsolete this term.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_prolate_traochoidal_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: prolate traochoidal mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer in which the ions of different m/z are separated by means of crossed electric and magnetic fields in such a way that the selected ions follow a prolate trochoidal path.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_paul_ion_trap
member.summary: paul ion trap: A device that permits the trapping of ions by means of an alternating current voltage. The ejection of ions with a m/z less than a prescribed value and retention of those with higher mass depends on the application of radio frequency voltages between a ring electrode and two end-cap electrodes to confine the ions in a circular path. The choice of these voltages determines the m/z below which ions are ejected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_nier_johnson_geometry
member.summary: nier-johnson geometry: An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/2 radians in a radial electric field analyzer is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/3 radians.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mattauch_herzog_geometry
member.summary: mattauch-herzog geometry: An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/(4 ?(2)) radians in a radial electric field is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/2 radians.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_spectrum
member.summary: mass spectrum: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: mass spectrometer: An instrument that measures the mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundances of ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_mass_spectrograph_obsolete
member.summary: mass spectrograph obsolete: An instrument that separates a beam of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio in which the ions are directed onto a focal plane detector such as a photographic plate.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_linear_ion_trap
member.summary: linear ion trap: A two dimensional Paul ion trap in which ions are confined in the axial dimension by means of an electric field at the ends of the trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_hybrid_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: hybrid mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that combines m/z analyzers of different types to perform tandem mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_double_focusing_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: double-focusing mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that uses a magnetic sector for m/z focusing and an electric sector for energy focusing of an ion beam.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.CVID.MS_cyclotron
member.summary: cyclotron: A device that uses an oscillating electric field and magnetic field to accelerate charged particles.
